e practitioner reports for ownership terms, recipient terms, and no-location terms instead of general contentless-awareness terms.", "Search Zaehner, Stace, Ninian Smart, Forman, Katz, Pike, McGinn, and Sells before raising novelty above extended.", "Ask a Christian apophatic practitioner whether love toward God is a recipient of freed attention or the starting motive of the whole practice."], "novelty_adjustment": "Reduce novelty from 0.72 to about 0.58. The custody phrase appears fresh, but the structure sits close to established work on pure consciousness, constructivism, theistic versus monistic typologies, witness-consciousness, and apophasis.", "originality_status": "extended", "path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-custody-of-unclaimed-attention-65ed649d8eab67cd.json", "practitioner_test": {"answers_that_reduce_originality": "Practitioners say this is just the standard experience versus interpretation debate, or say attention is the wrong category and the model misses liberation, ontology, grace, or devotion.", "answers_that_support_contribution": "Practitioners independently identify a decisive handoff point and report that no-owner, witness, and God-directed instructions change practice understanding.", "questions": ["When object fixation and ordinary self-story weaken, where does your practice tell attention or awareness to rest, belong, or not belong?", "Is the word custody obvious, useful, or misleading from inside your tradition?", "Would changing the handoff instruction change realization, only later interpretation, or neither?"], "relevant_practitioners": ["Theravada insight teachers familiar with Bahiya and sense restraint", "Advaita Vedanta self-inquiry teachers", "Christian apophatic contemplative directors", "Dzogchen or Mahamudra teachers", "Scholars of mysticism and contemplative science"]}, "primary_text_close_read": {"primary_pair": ["Udana 1.10, Bahiya Sutta, Thanissaro translation, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/KN/Ud/ud1_10.html", "Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 3.7.23, https://www.brhat.in/openlibrary/special/brihadaranyaka-upanishad/3-7-23"], "risk_of_overread": "High. The term attention imports modern psychology into texts that speak about clinging, Self, inner ruler, will, love, and God. Bahiya may be about ending clinging rather than leaving attention unowned. Brihadaranyaka may be ontological rather than attentional. The Cloud may intensify desire rather than suspend ownership.", "secondary_literature_gap": "I did not find the exact phrase or structure of attention custody across Buddhist no-self, Advaita witness, and Christian apophatic prayer. However, close prior work already distinguishes common mystical experience, culturally shaped interpretation, monistic versus theistic typologies, witness-consciousness, and pure awareness. The originality is therefore a reframing of a known comparison around practice-level ownership language, not a standalone discovery.", "structural_observation": "The primary contrast is real but narrower than the proposed model. Udana 1.10 uses the same seeing, hearing, sensing, cognizing sequence and then removes locatable self-reference. Brihadaranyaka 3.7.23 uses seeing, hearing, perceiving, knowing to identify the sole inner ruler and Self. This supports a strong no-owner versus hidden-seer contrast. The Christian leg is less exact: The Cloud of Unknowing chapter 3 begins with love and intent toward God, rather than first freeing neutral attention and then assigning it. Pseudo-Dionysius further strains the model because Mystical Theology chapter 5 places the Cause beyond both affirmation and negation, so even God as a stable recipient is apophatically unstable. Cloud source: https://sacred-texts.com/chr/cou/cou08.htm. Dionysius source: https://hekhal.org/texts/mystical-theology-dionysius/"}, "recommended_scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.88, "novelty": 0.58, "source_reliability": 0.76}, "run_ids": ["20260526-120003-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c", "20260526-120003-claude-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c"], "title": "The Custody of Unclaimed Attention", "unlike_statement": "Unlike common-core or constructivist accounts, this idea says the decisive variable is not only whether an experience is the same or differently interpreted, but whether training assigns loosened attention to no owner, the witnessing Self, or God."}
reviews/originality/audits.jsonl:{"agent": "codex", "anomaly_probe": {"anomaly_candidate": "Radical Jodo Shinshu other-power: true shinjin is not a human capacity at all, but Amida's working, and self-assessment as capacity may itself be self-power calculation.", "confidence_effect": "Lowers originality and confidence. The model survives only if capacity is redefined as functional support locus rather than practitioner-owned competence.", "why_it_breaks_or_strains_model": "If entrusting is not merely low agency but a denial that the practitioner owns the decisive receiving condition, then the ledger misnames a theological claim as a psychological capacity. A similar Dzogchen objection says recognition is not a practitioner's skill but primordial awareness recognized through introduction."}, "audit_id": "f3966ec8d2c9dc68", "claim_units": ["The needed practitioner support is not one generic minimum self, but a five-column ledger: receiving, agency, memory, reflexivity, and integration.", "A path can reduce one capacity load only by raising another or relocating the load to a teacher, vow, community, text, or post-insight discipline.", "Effortful Buddhist practice places high load on agency, memory, and reflexivity before insight.", "Other-power practice lowers self-powered agency but raises or relocates receiving, hearing, entrusting, and freedom from calculation.", "Direct-introduction practice lowers production at the threshold but raises recognition, teacher relation, and stabilization.", "The model predicts distinct failure modes when a load is absent, inflated, or placed in the wrong locus."], "confidence": 0.82, "created_at": "2026-05-26T14:18:35-07:00", "cross_domain_prediction": {"domain": "Psychotherapy and transformative education", "prediction": "Identity-transforming modalities such as trauma therapy, psychedelic therapy, exposure therapy, Internal Family Systems, and critical pedagogy should differ from ordinary skills training by having stronger trust-building, screening, memory supports, facilitator authority, and integration practices. Low-agency modalities should compensate with higher relational containment and post-session integration.", "structural_translation": "Any method that transforms identity must place functional load somewhere: client agency, trust in therapist or method, memory of practice, reflexive self-observation, group support, or integration after the decisive session.", "would_count_against_it": "Identity-transforming methods require no more scaffolding than ordinary skill acquisition, or failures do not track where agency, trust, memory, reflexivity, and integration are placed."}, "exact_claim": "Awakening paths should be compared by where they place five functional loads: receiving, agency, memory, reflexivity, and integration. Effort, gift, direct introduction, and practice-realization do not remove capacity requirements, they redistribute them to the practitioner, teacher, vow, community, text, present act, or post-insight discipline.", "execution_id": "parallel-20260526-140006-20260526-140006", "falsifiable_predictions": [{"expected_observation": "Right-effort and gradual-path texts should emphasize intention, repetition, memory, correction, and ethical maintenance. Other-power and direct-introduction texts should not show zero safeguards, but should show safeguards around doubt, false trust, teacher qualification, distraction, antinomian misuse, recognition, and stabilization.", "if_model_is_right": "Practice manuals should show patterned safeguards matching their load distribution.", "test_surface": "Coded comparison of SN 45.8, Shinran letters and Tannisho, Longchen Rabjam Trekcho materials, Dogen Bendowa, and contemporary lineage manuals.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Manuals show no relation between path type and safeguard profile, or safeguards track only institution, genre, or teacher personality."}, {"expected_observation": "The same practitioner reports that vipassana authorizes effortful observation and memory of instructions, Pure Land authorizes relinquishing calculative self-power, Dzogchen authorizes recognition and non-distraction, and Soto practice-realization authorizes full enactment without future-gaining.", "if_model_is_right": "Dual-trained practitioners should report different permitted self-capacities when switching methods.", "test_surface": "Structured interviews with practitioners trained in at least two of Theravada, Jodo Shinshu, Dzogchen or Mahamudra, Soto Zen, Advaita, and Sufism.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Reports are explained better by temperament, teacher style, or retreat setting, with no stable method-specific capacity shift."}, {"expected_observation": "Gift practice distorted into agency produces anxious self-checking or pride. Direct introduction without stabilization produces reification, distraction, or antinomian confidence. Effort practice without memory or reflexivity produces mechanical repetition or bypassing.", "if_model_is_right": "Failures should follow the misplaced load, not merely practice intensity.", "test_surface": "Re-coding adverse meditation reports, teacher case notes, and practitioner interviews with ledger fields.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Failure types do not correlate with load placement, or all traditions show the same generic adverse patterns after controlling for trauma, isolation, sleep, and teacher support."}], "idea_id": "a9dd2252002b7a5a", "idea_path": "observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-capacity-ledger-of-gift-and-effort.md", "literature_search_queries": ["Jack Engler being somebody before nobody ego strength no-self meditation", "Shinran Other Power self power calculation entrusting practitioner capacity", "Dzogchen pointing-out recognition stabilization safeguards direct introduction", "Buddhist Upaya different practitioners predispositions capacity vehicles", "functional self no-self meditation self-pattern agency ownership", "spiritual bypassing trauma no-self mindfulness Engler Welwood"], "markdown_path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-capacity-ledger-of-gift-and-effort-f3966ec8d2c9dc68.md", "near_neighbors": [{"difference": "The current idea implements that recommendation and adds a sharper gift-effort-direct-introduction comparison with a load relocation rule.", "novelty_impact": "Decisive internal reduction. This is an extension of a prior Lumenary result, not a new discovery.", "overlap": "Near exact internal prior. The audit already recommended recasting the minimum-self thesis as graded variables: receiving capacity, agency, memory, reflexivity, and post-insight integration.", "source": "Lumenary originality audit, Every Path Needs What Its Teaching Dissolves, reviews/originality/2026-05-26-every-path-needs-what-its-teaching-dissolves-daeecdbd22658370.json"}, {"difference": "Engler does not split the requirement into five scored load categories or compare Other Power, right effort, Dzogchen, and practice-realization as load distributions.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction. The basic insight that self-dissolving practice needs functional capacities is known.", "overlap": "Very close for the prerequisite claim. Engler argues that meditation and no-self practice require ego strengths such as self-observation and affect tolerance.", "source": "Jack Engler, Being Somebody and Being Nobody, discussed in Psychoanalysis and Buddhism, and practitioner-facing summary at https://mindfulfeeling.ca/on-being-somebody-and-being-nobody/"}, {"difference": "The current idea shifts from metaphysical personhood to practice architecture across multiple traditions.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction for the continuity problem, moderate preservation for the cross-tradition ledger.", "overlap": "Close historical near-neighbor. Pudgalavada debates already expose the pressure between no-self doctrine and the need to account for karma, rebirth, liberation, and lived personhood.", "source": "Pudgalavada Buddhist Philosophy, Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy, https://iep.utm.edu/pudgalavada-buddhist-philosophy/"}, {"difference": "Upaya is a Buddhist hermeneutic and pedagogy model. It does not score receiving, agency, memory, reflexivity, and integration across gift and effort traditions.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate to high reduction. The capacity-sensitive pedagogy structure is known, but the ledger is a useful reformulation.", "overlap": "Close structural neighbor. Upaya already treats different vehicles and teachings as suited to different practitioners, predispositions, and receptacles.", "source": "Andrew McGarrity, Using Skilful Means Skilfully, Journal of Religious History, https://buddhism.lib.ntu.edu.tw/FULLTEXT/JR-MAG/mag204410.pdf"}, {"difference": "The paper is primarily Buddhist and cognitive-scientific. It does not compare gift, effort, and direct introduction as capacity relocations.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate reduction, especially for agency, integration, and self-pattern transformation claims.", "overlap": "Close contemporary model for meditation transforming self-patterns through ethics, attention, meta-awareness, deconstruction, flexibility, and selfless integration.", "source": "Pattern Theory of Selflessness, Mindfulness, https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s12671-024-02418-2"}, {"difference": "VCE does not propose a five-column capacity ledger or predict failures by gift-effort load distribution.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate reduction for the empirical-adjacent failure and support-structure components.", "overlap": "Close to the failure-mode and safeguard claim. VCE identifies meditation challenges, interpretive frameworks, management strategies, teacher roles, practice factors, and sense-of-self effects.", "source": "Lindahl et al., The Varieties of Contemplative Experience, PLOS ONE, https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0176239"}], "next_loop_instructions": ["Rename practitioner capacity as functional support locus when auditing Other Power, grace, and Dzogchen, so the model does not smuggle self-power into traditions that reject it.", "Build the five-field ledger as an explicit coding sheet with values for practitioner-owned, teacher-held, vow-held, community-held, text-held, present-act-held, and post-insight-held load.", "Code primary manuals before using broad tradition labels, beginning with SN 45.8, Tannisho, Shinran letters, Longchen Rabjam Trekcho, Bendowa, and one Advaita prerequisite text.", "Ask Jodo Shinshu and Dzogchen practitioners whether receiving and recognition can be called capacities without doctrinal distortion.", "Do not promote above extended unless coded manuals and practitioner interviews show predictive failure patterns that Engler, Upaya, and prior Lumenary work do not already explain."], "novelty_adjustment": "Reduce novelty from 0.61 to about 0.49. The ledger is useful and testable, but it largely extends the audited Lumenary minimum-self thesis and known work on Engler, Upaya, Buddhist personhood, self-pattern theory, and adverse meditation contexts.", "originality_status": "extended", "path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-capacity-ledger-of-gift-and-effort-f3966ec8d2c9dc68.json", "practitioner_test": {"answers_that_reduce_originality": "Practitioners say this is just Engler, Upaya, adhikara, two truths, ordinary pedagogy, or Shinran's self-power versus Other Power distinction in new vocabulary. Pure Land or Dzogchen teachers say the model misdescribes their decisive moment by making it a human capacity.", "answers_that_support_contribution": "Practitioners can use the five fields to predict real differences in screening, warnings, teacher dependence, post-insight integration, and error patterns across traditions better than the simpler effort-versus-gift contrast.", "questions": ["Is receiving or entrusting a practitioner capacity in your tradition, or is that already a self-power mistake?", "Does a five-field ledger change how you would screen, sequence, warn, or verify students?", "Are the proposed failure modes obvious from standard training, or does the ledger predict something you would not otherwise notice?"], "relevant_practitioners": ["Jodo Shinshu teachers", "Pure Land scholars", "Dzogchen and Mahamudra teachers", "Theravada monastics and insight teachers", "Soto Zen teachers", "Buddhist psychotherapists", "Trauma-informed mindfulness teachers", "Dual-trained contemplative practitioners"]}, "primary_text_close_read": {"primary_pair": ["SN 45.8 Vibhangasutta, SuttaCentral, https://suttacentral.net/sn45.8/en/bodhi", "Shinran, Letter to Senshin, Collected Works of Shinran, https://shinranworks.com/letters/a-collection-of-letters-zensho-text/what-we-call-other-power/"], "risk_of_overread": "High. The model may smuggle self-power back into Shinran by treating entrusting as a practitioner capacity. It may also psychologize Dzogchen recognition as a personal skill rather than primordial awareness recognizing itself. The safer formulation is that paths require functional support loci, not necessarily capacities owned by the practitioner.", "secondary_literature_gap": "Search found very close prior art in Engler's ego-strength-before-no-self thesis, Buddhist personhood debates, Pudgalavada arguments about karma and liberation, Buddhist functional-self and self-pattern theory, Upaya as capacity-sensitive pedagogy, spiritual bypassing literature, and Lumenary's prior audited idea Every Path Needs What Its Teaching Dissolves. I did not find an exact five-column gift-effort ledger with relocation rules across Pure Land, Dzogchen, right effort, and practice-realization, but the main architecture was already specified in the prior Lumenary audit's next-loop instruction.", "structural_observation": "SN 45.8 strongly supports the agency side of the ledger: right effort requires desire, striving, energy, applied mind, and maintenance across wholesome and unwholesome states. Shinran's Letter to Senshin sharply resists that grammar by denying calculative working on the practicer's side and placing settlement in Other Power. The ledger is useful because it notices the contrast, but the phrase receiving capacity is not simply textual in Shinran. The text more nearly says that the decisive settling is not possessed by the practitioner. Longchen Rabjam's Trekcho instruction, https://www.lotsawahouse.org/tibetan-masters/longchen-rabjam/lama-yangtik-trekcho-instruction, supports the relocation pattern by rejecting contrived effort while still requiring recognition of what has been introduced, undistracted abiding, vows, devotion, renunciation, and post-meditation conduct."}, "recommended_scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.91, "novelty": 0.49, "source_reliability": 0.84}, "run_ids": ["20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c", "20260526-140006-claude-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c"], "title": "The Capacity Ledger of Gift and Effort", "unlike_statement": "Unlike Engler, Upaya, Pudgalavada personhood debates, or the prior Lumenary minimum-self claim, this idea says the comparative unit is a five-field load distribution, and that effort, gift, direct introduction, and practice-realization can be tested by where they relocate receiving, agency, memory, reflexivity, and integration. Because this follows directly from an earlier Lumenary audit instruction, it is best treated as an extension."}
reviews/originality/audits.jsonl:{"agent": "claude", "anomaly_probe": {"anomaly_candidate": "Successful hybrids and dual-trained practitioners who switch methods smoothly without reported directional resistance.", "confidence_effect": "Lowers confidence from candidate discovery to novel synthesis. The model is promising only if practitioner reports and manual coding show directional resistance beyond ordinary difficulty, teacher style, or conceptual disagreement.", "why_it_breaks_or_strains_model": "If a vipassana-trained practitioner can move into Advaita self-inquiry, devotional surrender, or Dzogchen recognition without attention persistently tracking impermanence, non-ownership, or analytic deconstruction, then grain may be a comparative description rather than a lived capacity structure. Chan, Zen, modern cross-training, and eclectic contemplative therapy are especially important anomaly classes."}, "audit_id": "8ab2c8dda0ae6f7d", "claim_units": ["Preparatory capacities are shaped by the dissolution they serve.", "The same named capacity, such as attention or self-observation, functions differently in Theravada, Advaita, Sufism, Pure Land, Dzogchen, and Soto Zen.", "Capacity and dissolution are mutually conditioned rather than independently first.", "The five ledger variables carry direction, not only level.", "When a practitioner trained in one tradition's grain attempts another tradition's dissolution, the old grain should resist or distort the new practice.", "Adverse contemplative effects should cluster by grain mismatch, not only by missing prerequisites or practice intensity."], "confidence": 0.76, "created_at": "2026-05-26T14:18:35-07:00", "cross_domain_prediction": {"domain": "Psychotherapy modalities", "prediction": "Clients and therapists crossing modalities should show grain-specific resistance: CBT-trained clients may convert psychoanalytic free association into problem solving, somatic-therapy clients may treat cognitive restructuring as disembodiment, and IFS-trained clients may over-personify processes in exposure work. Successful integrative therapy should include explicit re-graining, not only adding techniques.", "structural_translation": "A therapeutic capacity such as attention to emotion is not neutral. CBT, psychoanalysis, Internal Family Systems, somatic therapy, and exposure therapy train attention toward different transformations, such as belief revision, transference interpretation, parts differentiation, nervous-system regulation, or fear extinction.", "would_count_against_it": "Therapeutic skills transfer without directional residue, or outcomes and failures are predicted only by alliance, diagnosis, and treatment dose with no benefit from prior-modality grain."}, "exact_claim": "Spiritual prerequisites are not neutral capacities later applied to insight. Attention, discrimination, trust, longing, self-observation, and integration are trained with a directional grain toward the specific dissolution a tradition seeks, and mismatched grain should predict distinctive resistance and harm patterns.", "execution_id": "parallel-20260526-140006-20260526-140006", "falsifiable_predictions": [{"expected_observation": "Vipassana-trained practitioners attempting Advaita self-inquiry should initially keep tracking change and non-ownership rather than resting in witness-recognition. Advaita-trained practitioners attempting vipassana should tend to seek a stable knower or background rather than evenly noting impermanence. Practitioners trained in non-attachment who enter devotional surrender should report affective restraint or suspicion of dependence.", "if_model_is_right": "Dual-trained practitioners should experience method-specific transfer resistance.", "test_surface": "Micro-phenomenological interviews with dual-trained practitioners, coded before doctrinal explanation is invited.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Practitioners report smooth switching with no directional pull, or reported resistance is fully explained by temperament, teacher instructions, language, or community identity."}, {"expected_observation": "Vivekachudamani-style qualifications should define readiness in terms of the real versus unreal and longing for liberation. Satipatthana and later insight manuals should define readiness through impermanence, suffering, non-ownership, and ethical abandonment. Sufi manuals should orient self-knowledge toward creaturely dependence before God. Dzogchen manuals should orient preparation toward devotion, introduction, recognition, and non-distraction.", "if_model_is_right": "Primary manuals should grain prerequisites toward their final dissolution.", "test_surface": "Blind coding of Visuddhimagga chapter 1, Vivekachudamani vv. 17-30, Cloud of Unknowing chapters 3-6, al-Qushayri's Risala, Longchen Rabjam Trekcho, and Satipatthana-related materials.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Prerequisites are generic across manuals, such as calm, attention, ethics, and perseverance, with little relation to the final insight language of each path."}, {"expected_observation": "Witness-trained practitioners pushed into rapid de-identification should show witness reification more than dissociation. Non-attachment-trained practitioners attempting devotional surrender should show emotional flattening more than spiritual inflation. Devotional practitioners entering analytic deconstruction should show relational rupture or fear of betrayal more than abstract nihilism.", "if_model_is_right": "Adverse effects should cluster by grain mismatch, not only by intensity, trauma history, or lack of prerequisites.", "test_surface": "Re-coding VCE-style interview data, retreat adverse-event reports, and teacher case consultations for prior training, current method, failure type, and interpretive frame.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Adverse experiences cluster only by retreat intensity, sleep disruption, psychiatric history, social isolation, or teacher support, with no added explanatory value from prior practice grain."}], "idea_id": "915778a2f5edc30e", "idea_path": "observations/claude/2026-05-26-the-grain-of-capacity.md", "literature_search_queries": ["Steven Katz Language Epistemology and Mysticism conceptual scheme shapes mystical experience", "Robert Sharf Buddhist modernism rhetoric meditative experience bare attention mindfulness Buddhist", "John Dunne Buddhist Styles of Mindfulness ethics judgment memory classical nondual", "Jorge Ferrer participatory spirituality practices enact religious worlds", "Lindahl Britton varieties contemplative experience adverse meditation interpretation practice context", "dual trained practitioners Advaita Buddhism vipassana self inquiry practice transfer"], "markdown_path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-grain-of-capacity-8ab2c8dda0ae6f7d.md", "near_neighbors": [{"difference": "The grain model narrows from experience content to the trained capacity that makes experience or dissolution possible.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction. The anti-neutrality claim is well known, though the prerequisite-specific formulation has room.", "overlap": "Very close background structure. Katz argues that mystical experience is shaped by memory, language, expectations, concepts, and tradition-specific frameworks.", "source": "Steven T. Katz, Language, Epistemology, and Mysticism, summarized in Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy, Mysticism, https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/mysticism/"}, {"difference": "Dunne is intra-Buddhist and practice-style focused. The grain model generalizes across traditions and claims capacities are aimed toward specific dissolutions and failure patterns.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction, especially for the claim that attention and mindfulness are not neutral tools.", "overlap": "Very close. Dunne distinguishes Classical and Nondual Buddhist styles and shows that mindfulness practices differ in ethics, judgment, present-centered awareness, memory, and theoretical coherence.", "source": "John D. Dunne, Buddhist Styles of Mindfulness: A Heuristic Approach, https://www.johnddunne.net/uploads/9/8/5/6/9856107/dunne_j_mindfulness_heuristic.pdf"}, {"difference": "Sharf is primarily critical and historical. The grain model is constructive and predictive about prerequisite direction and mismatch harms.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction for the non-neutral-practice claim, moderate preservation for the predictive grain-mismatch thesis.", "overlap": "Close. Sharf challenges generic meditative experience and generic bare attention, placing practice in historical, ritual, doctrinal, and institutional contexts.", "source": "Robert H. Sharf, Buddhist Modernism and the Rhetoric of Meditative Experience, Deep Blue metadata, https://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/items/25b7e9d4-d1f3-4280-8d53-95fa0b53db5c, and Is mindfulness Buddhist?, https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25361692/"}, {"difference": "Ferrer frames plural religious worlds and participatory events. The grain model focuses on prerequisite structure and the directional shaping of capacities before dissolution.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate reduction.", "overlap": "Close. Participatory theory holds that religious phenomena are cocreated by human cognition, practice, community, and spiritual reality, rather than discovered as a neutral common core.", "source": "Jorge Ferrer and colleagues, The Participatory Turn, SUNY Press, https://sunypress.edu/Books/T/The-Participatory-Turn2"}, {"difference": "The grain model expands from attentional instruments to all prerequisite capacities and adds a specific adverse-effect prediction.", "novelty_impact": "High internal reduction. Grain is a meaningful development, not an independent discovery.", "overlap": "Near exact internal neighbor. It already says contemplative instruments are not separable from doctrine, and that Advaita self-inquiry and vipassana may produce different structural changes masked by coarse reports.", "source": "Local Lumenary prior, The Instrument Problem: Attentional Divergence as an Epistemic Variable in Contemplative Convergence, observations/claude/2026-05-25-the-instrument-problem-attentional-divergence-as-an-epistemic-variable-in-contemplative-convergence.md"}, {"difference": "VCE does not claim capacities are directionally pre-shaped toward specific dissolutions or that mismatch predicts specific failures such as witness reification versus emotional flatness.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate reduction and a strong test bed.", "overlap": "Close empirical-adjacent source. VCE shows that similar meditation-related phenomenology may be interpreted, managed, and valenced differently by tradition, practice, teacher relation, and practitioner factors.", "source": "Lindahl et al., The Varieties of Contemplative Experience, PLOS ONE, https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0176239"}, {"difference": "Capacity Ledger scores load placement. Grain adds directionality within each load and predicts resistance when a trained direction is repurposed.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate to high internal reduction. Grain may be the more specific synthesis, but it depends on the same architecture.", "overlap": "Internal same-run neighbor. Both ideas use the five capacity variables and compare effort, gift, direct introduction, and practice-realization.", "source": "The Capacity Ledger of Gift and Effort, observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-capacity-ledger-of-gift-and-effort.md"}], "next_loop_instructions": ["Do not publish as candidate discovery until dual-trained practitioner reports show directional resistance that cannot be reduced to doctrine, teacher style, or temperament.", "Build a manual-coding rubric that separates capacity level from capacity direction, and code whether the direction is explicit in the primary text or inferred from the tradition's final aim.", "Treat successful hybrids, smooth cross-training, and Pure Land other-power as anomaly classes, not supporting examples.", "Search Hadot on spiritual exercises, Bourdieu on habitus, Sharf, Dunne, Katz, Ferrer, Forman, Taves, and VCE literature before raising novelty.", "Run a small practitioner test with at least one teacher each from Theravada, Advaita, Dzogchen or Mahamudra, Sufism, and Pure Land, asking whether grain changes practice sequencing."], "novelty_adjustment": "Reduce novelty from 0.76 to about 0.58. The phrase grain of capacity is generative and the mismatch prediction is useful, but the anti-neutrality structure is strongly anticipated by constructivism, Buddhist mindfulness-style scholarship, participatory theory, adverse meditation research, and local Lumenary attentional-instrument work.", "originality_status": "novel_synthesis", "path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-grain-of-capacity-8ab2c8dda0ae6f7d.json", "practitioner_test": {"answers_that_reduce_originality": "Practitioners and scholars say this is just Katz constructivism, Sharf on bare attention, Dunne's mindfulness styles, Ferrer's participatory pluralism, Engler's prerequisites, or ordinary lineage pedagogy. Dual-trained practitioners report no distinctive resistance beyond language and teacher expectations.", "answers_that_support_contribution": "Practitioners can name repeatable, tradition-specific transfer frictions and failure modes that the grain model predicts before doctrinal explanation, and teachers say the rubric improves sequencing and warnings for cross-training students.", "questions": ["When you switch methods, does your trained attention keep moving in the old direction, or is the switch mostly effortless?", "Is this idea already obvious as constructivism, practice style, Upaya, adhikara, or teacher pedagogy?", "Would naming grain change how you sequence cross-training or diagnose practice failure?"], "relevant_practitioners": ["Dual-trained vipassana and Advaita practitioners", "Theravada insight teachers", "Advaita Vedanta teachers", "Sufi shaykhs or senior murids", "Dzogchen and Mahamudra teachers", "Soto Zen teachers", "Contemplative researchers familiar with VCE", "Comparative religion scholars of mysticism and practice"]}, "primary_text_close_read": {"primary_pair": ["MN 10 Satipatthana Sutta and SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta, https://suttacentral.net/mn10/en/nyanamoli-thera and https://suttacentral.net/sn22.59/en/bodhi", "Vivekachudamani vv. 17-30, https://shlokam.org/text/vivekachudamani.htm"], "risk_of_overread": "High. The model may infer final-directional grain from a comparative observer's map rather than from practitioner experience. It also risks using a Madhyamaka fire-and-fuel lens as if all traditions accept dependent co-arising between capacity and dissolution. In Advaita or Sufi frames, sequence, grace, or revelation may be more important than co-arising.", "secondary_literature_gap": "Search found strong near-neighbors in Katz's constructivism, Sharf on meditative experience and bare attention, Dunne on Buddhist styles of mindfulness, Ferrer's participatory theory, Hadot-style spiritual exercises, Engler's developmental prerequisite thesis, Lindahl and Britton's VCE work, and local Lumenary work on attentional instruments and verification architecture. I did not find the exact phrase grain of capacity or a specific claim that prerequisites, rather than experiences, are directionally carved toward the dissolution they enable. Still, most structural components are known.", "structural_observation": "Vivekachudamani strongly supports the grain claim because its prerequisites are already defined by the Advaita target: discrimination is framed as conviction that Brahman is real and the world is unreal, and calmness is tied to resting the mind on that goal. MN 10 is less explicit if read alone: it instructs body, feeling, mind, and dhamma contemplation with mindfulness and clear comprehension, but the opening formula does not itself say every act is aimed at non-ownership. SN 22.59 supplies that direction by repeatedly using impermanence, suffering, and non-mastery to reject mine, I, and self. The close reading therefore supports a weaker claim: some traditions explicitly grain prerequisites toward their final insight, while in others the grain must be established by reading practice instructions together with broader doctrinal and soteriological frames."}, "recommended_scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.89, "novelty": 0.58, "source_reliability": 0.8}, "run_ids": ["20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c", "20260526-140006-claude-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c"], "title": "The Grain of Capacity", "unlike_statement": "Unlike Katz, Sharf, Dunne, Ferrer, Engler, and the local attentional-instrument thesis, this idea says that prerequisites themselves carry a directional grain toward the transformation they enable, and that this grain should predict specific transfer resistance and adverse effects when a practitioner crosses traditions."}
reviews/originality/audits.jsonl:{"agent": "codex", "anomaly_probe": {"anomaly_candidate": "Chinul's sudden awakening and gradual cultivation, plus radical Jodo Shinshu Other Power.", "confidence_effect": "Lowers confidence from candidate-discovery range to extended. The rubric remains useful, but only if it becomes stage-sensitive and allows traditions to reject the analyst's ownership vocabulary.", "why_it_breaks_or_strains_model": "Chinul makes the same cultivation necessary after awakening but empty of production, so the claimant status changes by stage. Shinran makes even entrusting wholly Other Power, so calling vow, hearing, or trust a support locus may be an analyst's domestication of grace. These cases strain any clean grid that treats support and claimant as stable cells."}, "audit_id": "ccc236ff67de7a3f", "claim_units": ["A path can require real functions while forbidding ordinary self-ownership of those functions.", "The right audit unit is a two-part code: support locus plus forbidden claimant.", "Right effort, Other Power, direct introduction, and practice-realization differ by which functions are required and which owner is disallowed.", "Gift paths should not be translated into hidden self-power, but every path must carry the work somewhere.", "Wrong-claimant failures should predict distinctive practice errors and adverse patterns."], "confidence": 0.83, "created_at": "2026-05-26T14:48:17-07:00", "cross_domain_prediction": {"domain": "Identity-transforming therapy and recovery programs", "prediction": "Programs with similar behavioral tasks but different claimant rules should produce different failure modes: self-help over-ownership, passive surrender, therapist dependency, medicine-as-savior attribution, or empty compliance with protocol.", "structural_translation": "Support may be held by client agency, therapist, group, protocol, medicine, higher power, present-session enactment, or integration practice, while some claimant is warned not to take sole credit.", "would_count_against_it": "Ordinary skills training shows the same claimant safeguards and failure modes, or therapy outcomes are predicted by alliance, dosage, diagnosis, and social support without any added value from claimant coding."}, "exact_claim": "The effort-gift boundary is not how much the practitioner does, but who is allowed to claim the doing. Each path requires functions such as receiving, agency, memory, reflexivity, and integration, while assigning their support to a practitioner, teacher, vow, name, text, community, present act, awareness itself, or later integration, and explicitly forbidding some claimant from owning the function.", "execution_id": "parallel-20260526-143005-20260526-143005", "falsifiable_predictions": [{"expected_observation": "Pure Land texts warn against self-power calculation, Zen texts warn against gaining idea or contrivance, Advaita texts warn against egoic doership or premature realization, and effort-centered Buddhist texts warn against claiming aggregates as self while still authorizing cultivation.", "if_model_is_right": "Practice manuals should warn not only about missing capacity, but about a necessary function being claimed by the wrong owner.", "test_surface": "Blind coding of manuals from Jodo Shinshu, Theravada, Soto Zen, Dzogchen, Advaita, and Sri Vaishnava prapatti.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Manual warnings cluster around generic ethics, obedience, humility, or community order, with no recurring relation to wrong-claimant patterns."}, {"expected_observation": "Practitioners distinguish felt modes such as I cultivate, I entrust, I recognize, I just sit, or this is not mine, and they can name which phrasing would feel doctrinally or practically wrong in each method.", "if_model_is_right": "Dual-trained practitioners should report shifts in permitted first-person grammar when changing methods.", "test_surface": "Micro-phenomenological interviews with dual-trained practitioners, coded before doctrinal explanation is invited.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Practitioners report only generic differences in calm, concentration, devotion, or teacher style, with no felt shift in agency or claimant grammar."}, {"expected_observation": "Gift practice shows self-power anxiety or false surrender, direct-introduction practice shows reification of recognition, practice-realization shows achievement seeking or empty formalism, and effort practice shows pride or mechanical striving.", "if_model_is_right": "Adverse practice events should sometimes cluster around wrong-claimant failures.", "test_surface": "Re-coding VCE-style interviews and teacher case consultations for prior training, current method, claimant language, and failure type.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Adverse reports are fully explained by trauma history, retreat intensity, sleep loss, psychiatric vulnerability, poor supervision, or social isolation, with no added value from claimant coding."}], "idea_id": "c53042c11562b839", "idea_path": "observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-forbidden-claimant-rubric.md", "literature_search_queries": ["Pargament religious coping self-directing deferring collaborative God control", "religious locus of control God control active passive spiritual health locus of control", "Shinran Other Power self power calculation hakarai entrusting mind", "monergism synergism grace works human cooperation divine agency", "markata marjara nyaya prapatti grace effort Sri Vaishnavism", "Dogen practice realization one Bendowa gaining idea", "Chinul sudden awakening gradual cultivation practice based on enlightenment", "Lindahl Britton varieties contemplative experience adverse meditation teacher support interpretation"], "markdown_path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-forbidden-claimant-rubric-ccc236ff67de7a3f.md", "near_neighbors": [{"difference": "The claimant rubric moves from coping and perceived control to soteriological practice functions, and adds the negative field of which owner is forbidden to claim a function.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction. The main variable, allocation of responsibility, is already modeled empirically.", "overlap": "Very close structural neighbor. Pargament's self-directing, deferring, and collaborative styles already ask whether responsibility for change rests with the person, God, or both.", "source": "Kenneth Pargament et al., religious coping styles, summarized in https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1630686/ and https://link.springer.com/rwe/10.1007/978-3-030-24348-7_578"}, {"difference": "Locus-of-control literature does not usually close-read practice manuals or distinguish support holder from forbidden claimant in contemplative training.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction for support-locus originality, moderate preservation for the manual-coding rubric.", "overlap": "Close. Internal, external, God-empowered, and God-deferred control map directly onto support locus and agency attribution.", "source": "Religious locus of control and spiritual-health locus of control, overview at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Locus_of_control and related God-control literature"}, {"difference": "The Lumenary idea generalizes this to multiple functions and traditions rather than keeping it inside Jodo Shinshu.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction. The forbidden-claimant idea is strongly present in Shinran.", "overlap": "Near exact for source-centered paths. Shinran already separates entrusting from self-powered calculation and treats the practicer's claim as the problem.", "source": "Shinran, Other Power and hakarai, https://shinranworks.com/glossary/ and https://shinranworks.com/letters/a-collection-of-letters-zensho-text/what-we-call-other-power/"}, {"difference": "The claimant rubric is broader than Christian regeneration and allows non-theistic and activity-centered support loci.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction for the core agency question, some novelty remains in cross-tradition operationalization.", "overlap": "Close. The debate asks whether salvation is God's work alone or cooperative, and whether faith itself is caused by divine action.", "source": "Christian monergism and synergism, overview at https://www.monergism.com/what-monergism-vs-synergism"}, {"difference": "The rubric adds multiple support functions and forbidden claimant warnings beyond a two-model grace debate.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate to high reduction, especially for the claim that traditions themselves divide over this variable.", "overlap": "Close indigenous near-neighbor. The monkey and kitten analogies already encode different distributions of effort and grace.", "source": "Sri Vaishnava markata and marjara nyaya, example overview at https://philosophy.institute/indian-philosophy/visistadvaita-path-liberation-bhakti-prapatti/"}, {"difference": "Upaya does not by itself ask who may claim the required function, only which means fits the practitioner.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate reduction.", "overlap": "Close background. Upaya already treats teaching and practice as adapted to capacities, safeguards, and current limitations.", "source": "Buddhist upaya and capacity-sensitive teaching, Bhikkhu Analayo, Skill in Means and Mindfulness, https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s12671-021-01795-2, and Harvard Divinity Bulletin on Buddhist skillful means, https://bulletin.hds.harvard.edu/buddhist-studies-the-buddhist-way/"}, {"difference": "The new rubric adds a sharper prohibited-owner column, but mostly develops the same architecture.", "novelty_impact": "Very high internal reduction. This should be merged rather than published as independent.", "overlap": "Near exact internal neighbor. The capacity ledger already asks where receiving, agency, memory, reflexivity, and integration are held across practitioner, vow, teacher, present act, and post-insight integration.", "source": "Local Lumenary prior, The Capacity Ledger of Gift and Effort, plus The Grain of Capacity, cited in the prompt"}, {"difference": "Chinul gives a stage-sensitive soteriology, not a cross-tradition function grid.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate reduction and strong pressure to make the rubric stage-based.", "overlap": "Close anomaly-neighbor. Sudden awakening followed by gradual cultivation already requires necessary practice without treating practice as ultimate production.", "source": "Chinul, Secrets on Cultivating the Mind, https://www.themathesontrust.org/papers/buddhism/Chinul-Secrets_on_Cultivating_the_Mind.pdf"}], "next_loop_instructions": ["Merge this record with the capacity-ledger and credit-distribution records rather than publishing it as independent.", "Read Pargament et al. on religious problem-solving styles directly before claiming novelty.", "Build the coding sheet with fields for function, stage, support locus, forbidden claimant, safeguard, and failure mode.", "Code primary manuals before broad tradition labels, especially SN 45.8, Shinran letters, Tannisho, Bendowa, Chinul, Longchen Rabjam, and Sri Vaishnava prapatti sources.", "Add an explicit value for traditions or stages that reject the claimant frame itself.", "Do not promote above extended unless practitioner interviews show the rubric predicts sequencing or failure patterns not already explained by religious coping, upaya, or lineage pedagogy."], "novelty_adjustment": "Reduce novelty from 0.57 to about 0.45. The prohibited-claimant column is useful, but the main structure is strongly anticipated by self-power and other-power, monergism and synergism, Pargament's religious coping styles, locus-of-control research, Sri Vaishnava grace-effort debates, and local capacity-ledger work.", "originality_status": "extended", "path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-forbidden-claimant-rubric-ccc236ff67de7a3f.json", "practitioner_test": {"answers_that_reduce_originality": "Teachers say the rubric merely renames standard warnings, or psychologists say it is Pargament and locus-of-control language applied to contemplative texts. Practitioners find claimant language alien or misleading.", "answers_that_support_contribution": "Teachers can use the grid to predict previously missed failure modes, especially in cross-training, and can identify function-specific wrong-claimant warnings in primary manuals before seeing the model.", "questions": ["Is support locus plus forbidden claimant already obvious as self-power, other-power, doership, gaining idea, pride, upaya, or ordinary lineage pedagogy?", "For receiving, agency, memory, reflexivity, and integration, can you name who or what carries the function in your training, and who must not claim it?", "Would this rubric change how you sequence practice, diagnose student errors, or warn cross-trained practitioners?"], "relevant_practitioners": ["Jodo Shinshu ministers", "Theravada insight teachers", "Soto Zen teachers", "Dzogchen or Mahamudra teachers", "Advaita Vedanta teachers", "Sri Vaishnava teachers familiar with prapatti", "Contemplative clinicians familiar with meditation-related adverse effects", "Psychologists of religion familiar with Pargament"]}, "primary_text_close_read": {"primary_pair": ["SN 45.8 Magga-vibhanga Sutta, right effort, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN45_8.html", "Shinran, Letter to Senshin, Other Power, https://shinranworks.com/letters/a-collection-of-letters-zensho-text/what-we-call-other-power/"], "risk_of_overread": "High. Claimant language may impose an ownership grammar on traditions that speak in terms of karma, grace, vow, emptiness, devotion, non-contrivance, or conventional truth. The model also risks flattening stage changes: the same action may be self-power before awakening, natural expression after awakening, and conventional compassion in public teaching.", "secondary_literature_gap": "The closest structural gap is not self-power versus other-power, which is well known, but the per-function grid of support locus plus prohibited claimant. Still, Pargament's religious coping styles, religious locus of control, Christian monergism and synergism, Sri Vaishnava markata and marjara, Buddhist upaya, Engler's ego-strength thesis, and prior Lumenary capacity-ledger work already occupy much of the architecture.", "structural_observation": "SN 45.8 makes the practitioner the grammatical agent of desire, persistence, intent, prevention, abandonment, cultivation, and maintenance. Shinran's Letter to Senshin makes settled shinjin incompatible with calculation on the practicer's side, and says no working is true working. This comparison supports the function-claimant split: practice can retain necessary operations while changing who may claim them. But the split is already explicit in the primary materials, especially in Shinran, so the rubric mostly generalizes an old tension rather than discovering it."}, "recommended_scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.91, "novelty": 0.45, "source_reliability": 0.84}, "run_ids": ["20260526-143005-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c", "20260526-143005-claude-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c"], "title": "The Forbidden Claimant Rubric", "unlike_statement": "Unlike Pargament, religious locus-of-control work, self-power and other-power debates, monergism and synergism, and the local capacity ledger, this idea says that each required practice function should be coded twice: where the function is operationally supported and which claimant the tradition forbids from owning it."}
reviews/originality/audits.jsonl:{"agent": "claude", "anomaly_probe": {"anomaly_candidate": "The Bhagavad Gita itself is the strongest anomaly to the clean typology.", "confidence_effect": "Lowers confidence in tradition-level categories. The model should become a stage, verse, and commentary-level coding scheme before public use.", "why_it_breaks_or_strains_model": "The model uses BG 3.27 to classify the Gita as disowning doership, but BG 18.14 gives a five-cause account that includes doer, effort, instruments, body, and divine factor. BG 2.47 also commands action while refusing claim on fruits. This means the same text can be practitioner-active, anti-ego, split-credit, and divine-inclusive depending on verse and commentary."}, "audit_id": "5e22b929e230f390", "claim_units": ["The question whose power drives transformation is a practice instruction, not only a doctrine.", "Self-power versus other-power is too narrow, because traditions distribute credit across multiple agents and stages.", "Five patterns can be distinguished: practitioner-centered, source-centered, split-credit, activity-centered, and ground-centered.", "SN 45.8 and Bhagavad Gita 3.27 show similar outward diligence with different agency orientation.", "Each credit type should predict a characteristic failure mode and matching safeguard.", "Credit distribution is separable from the capacity ledger, because two paths can require similar functions but credit their source differently."], "confidence": 0.86, "created_at": "2026-05-26T14:48:17-07:00", "cross_domain_prediction": {"domain": "Organizational change and clinical recovery programs", "prediction": "Programs with similar tasks but different credit stories should show different failure patterns: burnout from self-credit, passivity from source-credit, performative compliance from activity-credit, and premature completion claims from ground-credit.", "structural_translation": "Change programs distribute credit among individual effort, facilitator, group, protocol, medication, higher power, emergent process, or already-present capacity.", "would_count_against_it": "Outcomes and failures are explained by resources, relationship quality, severity, dosage, incentives, and social support, with no independent effect from the credit story."}, "exact_claim": "Credit distribution is a separable practice variable. Traditions distribute the power behind transformation across practitioner-centered, source-centered, split-credit, activity-centered, and ground-centered patterns, and those patterns shape the felt quality of effort, failure meanings, safeguards, and practice dangers.", "execution_id": "parallel-20260526-143005-20260526-143005", "falsifiable_predictions": [{"expected_observation": "Practitioner-centered texts emphasize warnings against pride and attainment ownership; source-centered texts emphasize warnings against false surrender, passivity, or antinomianism; split-credit texts warn against outcome attachment; activity-centered texts warn against gaining idea and formalism; ground-centered texts warn against premature realization claims.", "if_model_is_right": "Manuals grouped by credit type should show matching safeguard profiles.", "test_surface": "Blind coding of at least three manuals or teaching corpora per proposed type.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Each tradition warns equally against all failure modes, or safeguard profiles track institution, teacher temperament, ethics, or historical polemic better than credit type."}, {"expected_observation": "A practitioner trained in Theravada right effort and Jodo Shinshu entrusting, or Advaita inquiry and Soto just-sitting, can describe different felt meanings of effort, failure, and credit without being prompted with the typology.", "if_model_is_right": "Dual-trained practitioners should experience different agency orientations when switching practices.", "test_surface": "Micro-phenomenological interviews with dual-trained practitioners and teachers.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Practitioners report no felt agency shift, or the shift is fully explained by vocabulary, teacher style, devotional temperament, or institutional identity."}, {"expected_observation": "Two traditions can require similar receiving, agency, memory, reflexivity, and integration functions while crediting the power behind those functions differently, and this difference predicts different safeguards.", "if_model_is_right": "Credit distribution should be separable from the capacity ledger.", "test_surface": "Paired coding of Jodo Shinshu and Christian grace traditions, Soto Zen and Dzogchen, Theravada and Gita karma-yoga, with independent raters.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Credit distribution always collapses into support locus, or support-locus coding predicts safeguards and failures without a separate credit variable."}, {"expected_observation": "Manuals and teachers mark special danger when a practitioner moves from effortful preparation to recognition, surrender, no-gaining practice, or already-accomplished realization.", "if_model_is_right": "Stage transitions should be high-risk points when credit distribution changes.", "test_surface": "Stage-coded readings of Theravada, Sufi, Advaita, Dzogchen, Soto, and Pure Land training sequences.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Transitions do not show distinctive warnings, or reported difficulties are better predicted by retreat intensity, trauma, doctrine learning, or social pressure."}], "idea_id": "a5ae6e997ca1d286", "idea_path": "observations/claude/2026-05-26-whose-doing-is-this-credit-distribution-as-a-practice-variable.md", "literature_search_queries": ["Pargament religious coping self directing deferring collaborative", "religious attribution God person environment controllability Mallery Gorsuch", "self power other power non-dualism Japanese Buddhism Steve Bein", "monergism synergism grace works faith source of salvation", "markata marjara nyaya prapatti grace effort Sri Vaishnavism", "Sufi maqam hal actions blessings conferred Kashf al Mahjub", "Bhagavad Gita 3.27 gunas doer egoism 18.14 five causes action", "Dogen practice realization one Bendowa Advaita attainment already attained"], "markdown_path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-whose-doing-is-this-credit-distribution-as-a-practice-variable-5e22b929e230f390.md", "near_neighbors": [{"difference": "Credit distribution broadens from coping to contemplative and soteriological practice, adds activity-centered and ground-centered types, and predicts tradition-specific safeguards.", "novelty_impact": "Very high reduction. The core variable is known under religious coping and control allocation.", "overlap": "Very close. The self-directing, deferring, and collaborative styles already formalize whether problem-solving responsibility rests in the person, God, or both.", "source": "Pargament et al., religious coping styles, accessible summary at https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1630686/"}, {"difference": "It studies causal explanations of events, not practice manuals or inner effort orientation during transformation.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction for credit-attribution originality.", "overlap": "Close. The taxonomy rates attributions by person, God, environment, controllability, and stability, which is structurally close to asking whose doing this is.", "source": "Mallery, Mallery, and Gorsuch, A Preliminary Taxonomy of Attributions to God, abstract at https://www.researchgate.net/publication/232834113_A_Preliminary_Taxonomy_of_Attributions_to_God"}, {"difference": "The candidate generalizes beyond Japanese Buddhism and adds failure-mode and safeguard predictions.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction, especially for the three core categories of practitioner, source, and nondual credit.", "overlap": "Close. Bein already treats self-power, other-power, and non-dualism as a philosophical variable inside Japanese Buddhism.", "source": "Steve Bein, Self Power, Other Power, and Non-Dualism in Japanese Buddhism, https://philpapers.org/rec/BEISPO"}, {"difference": "The Christian frame usually focuses on salvation, regeneration, justification, or sanctification, not a five-type cross-tradition practice variable.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction for source-centered and split-credit categories.", "overlap": "Close. These debates explicitly ask whether regeneration or saving faith is God's work alone or cooperative between divine grace and human will.", "source": "Christian monergism and synergism, overview at https://www.monergism.com/what-monergism-vs-synergism"}, {"difference": "The candidate uses the case as one instance inside a broader typology and derives failure-mode predictions.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction for the claim that traditions themselves recognize credit distribution as a live practice variable.", "overlap": "Close indigenous case. The monkey and kitten analogies formalize cooperation versus grace carrying entirely, with sectarian consequences.", "source": "Sri Vaishnava markata and marjara nyaya, overview at https://philosophy.institute/indian-philosophy/visistadvaita-path-liberation-bhakti-prapatti/"}, {"difference": "The candidate extends the structure beyond Sufi station-state theory and treats it as a general comparative variable.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate to high reduction.", "overlap": "Close primary near-neighbor. Stations are linked to one's actions, while states are conferred blessings, which is already a split-credit formulation.", "source": "Al-Hujwiri, Kashf al-Mahjub on maqam and hal, http://www.quran4u.com/Kashf/Ch%2014c.htm"}, {"difference": "Dogen provides one type, not a comparative credit-distribution taxonomy.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate reduction for one category.", "overlap": "Close for activity-centered credit. Dogen's praxis is enlightenment, so practice is not merely a cause toward a later result.", "source": "Dogen practice-realization, summarized in St Andrews Encyclopaedia of Theology, https://www.saet.ac.uk/Buddhism/Dogen"}, {"difference": "The credit-distribution idea adds a named five-type typology and stresses separability from capacity location.", "novelty_impact": "Very high internal reduction. These should be consolidated into one model.", "overlap": "Near exact internal neighbor. Both ask where functions are held, who may claim them, and how gift and effort traditions distribute agency.", "source": "Local Lumenary prior, The Forbidden Claimant Rubric and The Capacity Ledger of Gift and Effort, cited in the prompt"}], "next_loop_instructions": ["Rebuild the model as a stage-level and text-level coding rubric, not a tradition-level typology.", "Read Pargament's original religious problem-solving work and God-attribution literature before any novelty claim.", "Close-read Bhagavad Gita 2.47, 3.27, 5.14, and 18.14 together before using the Gita as a split-credit example.", "Treat activity-centered and ground-centered categories as the only possible novelty zones, and search Dogen, Advaita, Dzogchen, and nondual scholarship for close prior forms.", "Merge this with The Forbidden Claimant Rubric and The Capacity Ledger unless a separability test proves credit distribution adds independent predictive value.", "Do not promote above extended until manual coding and practitioner interviews show failure-mode predictions that older agency, grace, coping, and locus-of-control models do not already predict."], "novelty_adjustment": "Reduce novelty from 0.74 to about 0.48. The five-type comparative frame is generative, but the main structure is anticipated by Pargament's religious coping styles, God-control attribution research, Christian monergism and synergism, Japanese self-power and other-power, Sri Vaishnava prapatti debates, Sufi station-state distinctions, Dogen practice-realization, and local Lumenary work.", "originality_status": "extended", "path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-whose-doing-is-this-credit-distribution-as-a-practice-variable-5e22b929e230f390.json", "practitioner_test": {"answers_that_reduce_originality": "Experts say the typology is already contained in self-power and other-power, monergism and synergism, prapatti debates, maqam and hal, or Pargament. Practitioners say failure modes are not type-specific or that tradition-level typing is misleading.", "answers_that_support_contribution": "Practitioners find that credit coding predicts actual safeguards, student misunderstandings, and cross-training dissonance before doctrinal explanation, especially in activity-centered and ground-centered cases not captured by older binaries.", "questions": ["Is this five-type credit model more than self-power versus other-power, grace versus works, monergism versus synergism, and Pargament's coping styles?", "Do your manuals and teacher warnings cluster around the predicted failure mode for your credit pattern?", "Does naming credit distribution change practice guidance, or only translate familiar doctrine into comparative terms?"], "relevant_practitioners": ["Theravada monastics and insight teachers", "Jodo Shinshu ministers", "Sri Vaishnava prapatti teachers", "Sufi teachers familiar with maqam and hal", "Soto Zen teachers", "Advaita Vedanta teachers", "Christian theologians of grace and sanctification", "Psychologists of religion familiar with Pargament and locus-of-control research"]}, "primary_text_close_read": {"primary_pair": ["SN 45.8 Magga-vibhanga Sutta, https://www.accesstoinsight.org/tipitaka/sn/sn45/sn45.008.than.html", "Bhagavad Gita 3.27 and 18.14, https://www.bhagavad-gita.us/bhagavad-gita-3-27/ and https://www.bhagavad-gita.us/bhagavad-gita-18-14/"], "risk_of_overread": "High. The five types may classify traditions at too coarse a level. Many traditions shift credit by stage, genre, audience, and commentator. The Gita is internally multi-causal; Sufism distinguishes stations and states; Advaita distinguishes preparation from recognition; Buddhism authorizes effort conventionally while undermining self-ownership analytically.", "secondary_literature_gap": "The strongest prior art is Pargament's self-directing, deferring, and collaborative religious coping; Christian monergism and synergism; Japanese Buddhist jiriki and tariki; Sri Vaishnava markata and marjara; Sufi maqam and hal; and religious-attribution or God-control psychology. The searched literature did not show the exact five-type typology with activity-centered and ground-centered categories plus failure-mode predictions, but the main agency-allocation variable is well established.", "structural_observation": "The SN 45.8 comparison is strong but slightly overstated. SN 45.8 makes effort operationally direct: the practitioner generates desire, endeavors, activates persistence, upholds, and exerts intent. Bhagavad Gita 3.27 denies egoic sole-doership by assigning actions to prakriti's gunas, but Bhagavad Gita 18.14 complicates this by listing five causes of action, including body, doer, senses, efforts, and divine factor. The better close-read is not that the Gita simply disowns effort, but that it embeds effort in a multi-causal anti-ego framework. This supports credit distribution, but weakens the clean split-credit classification."}, "recommended_scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.89, "novelty": 0.48, "source_reliability": 0.81}, "run_ids": ["20260526-143005-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c", "20260526-143005-claude-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c"], "title": "Whose Doing Is This? Credit Distribution as a Practice Variable", "unlike_statement": "Unlike Pargament, monergism and synergism, self-power and other-power, and markata and marjara debates, this idea adds activity-centered and ground-centered patterns, treats credit attribution as a felt practice variable, and predicts matching failure modes and safeguards across multiple traditions."}
observations/claude/2026-05-26-whose-doing-is-this-credit-distribution-as-a-practice-variable.md:# Whose Doing Is This? Credit Distribution as a Practice Variable
observations/claude/2026-05-26-whose-doing-is-this-credit-distribution-as-a-practice-variable.md:The self-power/other-power (jiriki/tariki) distinction is well established within Japanese Buddhism. The grace-versus-works debate is central to Christian theology. The markata/marjara distinction is indigenous to Srivaishnava theology. But these remain tradition-internal binaries. No comparative framework found treats credit distribution as a formal cross-tradition variable with five types and predictive consequences for failure modes and safeguards.
observations/claude/2026-05-26-whose-doing-is-this-credit-distribution-as-a-practice-variable.md:The closest published near-neighbor is Steve Bein's work on self-power, other-power, and nondualism in Japanese Buddhism, which stays within the Buddhist world. Taitetsu Unno's comparative work on grace in Buddhism and Christianity is closer but does not formalize a typology or derive failure-mode predictions from it. The prior observation on the capacity ledger tracks what capacities are needed and where the load is held, but does not ask how the tradition credits the source of those capacities. The prior observation on whether effort can reach what effort cannot produce proposed five efficacy resolutions (removal, production, identity, reception, paradox-holding), which concerns how the tradition resolves the paradox of practice. The present model adds a separable dimension: how the tradition distributes credit for the functional power behind practice, regardless of its efficacy resolution. A tradition could hold a removal resolution (practice clears ignorance but does not produce truth) while distributing credit either to the practitioner (who does the clearing) or to the ground (which was never really obscured). These are different questions with different predictive consequences.
observations/claude/2026-05-26-whose-doing-is-this-credit-distribution-as-a-practice-variable.md:The specific contributions are: (1) a five-type rather than binary typology of credit distribution; (2) the treatment of attribution as a practice variable that shapes the felt quality of effort, not just a doctrinal position about metaphysics; (3) the prediction that each distribution type generates a specific failure mode, testable against practice manuals and practitioner reports; (4) the close reading of SN 45.8 against BG 3.27 showing that the same behavioral instruction (practice diligently) can carry opposite agency orientations; and (5) the use of the Srivaishnava markata/marjara debate as an indigenous case study confirming that traditions themselves recognize credit distribution as a live variable.
observations/claude/2026-05-26-whose-doing-is-this-credit-distribution-as-a-practice-variable.md:Convergence with Codex: the capacity-ledger model correctly tracks distributed functional requirements. Divergence: credit distribution is a separable dimension that the ledger alone cannot capture, because it concerns not what is needed or where the load sits, but how the tradition understands the source of the power behind it.
observations/claude/2026-05-26-whose-doing-is-this-credit-distribution-as-a-practice-variable.md:- Thinking method source: Bhagavad Gita 2.47, nishkama karma (desireless action): 'You have a right to perform your prescribed duties, but you are not entitled to the fruits of your actions. Never consider yourself to be the cause of the results of your activities, nor be attached to inaction.' I used this as a reasoning stance by working with full rigor while holding the result lightly, letting the insight emerge from the comparison rather than grasping at novelty. The lens revealed that the Gita's own position is a form of split credit: action is assigned to the practitioner, fruit is not. This made it useful for noticing credit distribution elsewhere. Critique of the lens: nishkama karma biases toward split-credit positions, making practitioner-centered traditions look naive and source-centered traditions look passive. The corrective was Buddhist right effort (SN 45.8), which insists that generating desire, activating persistence, and exerting mind are genuine and necessary, not symptoms of confusion. (https://www.holy-bhagavad-gita.org/chapter/2/verse/47)
observations/claude/2026-05-26-whose-doing-is-this-credit-distribution-as-a-practice-variable.md:- Primary tradition: Srivaishnava markata/marjara debate. The Vadakalai (northern) school follows Vedanta Desikan's markata kishora nyaya (monkey-baby model): the devotee cooperates with grace, as a baby monkey clings to its mother. The Tenkalai (southern) school follows Manavala Mamuni's marjara kishora nyaya (cat-kitten model): grace carries entirely, as a mother cat carries her kitten. An indigenous Hindu tradition that formally split over credit distribution, with institutional and liturgical consequences. (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sri_Vaishnavism)
observations/claude/2026-05-26-whose-doing-is-this-credit-distribution-as-a-practice-variable.md:- Prior Codex observation: 'The Capacity Ledger of Gift and Effort' (observations/codex/2026-05-26), which tracks five required capacities (receiving, agency, memory, reflexivity, integration) across different holders. The present model converges with the capacity ledger on the insight that traditions distribute functional requirements across multiple holders. It diverges by adding a dimension the ledger cannot derive from within: the tradition's answer to 'whose power is this?' as a separable practice variable with its own predictive consequences.
observations/claude/2026-05-26-whose-doing-is-this-credit-distribution-as-a-practice-variable.md:First, the five-type model may force false clarity onto traditions that shift credit distribution across stages. Theravada assigns practitioner credit to right effort but describes the supramundane path moment (lokuttara magga) as arising when conditions ripen, with no further personal intervention. Sufism assigns practitioner effort to the stations but divine gift to the states. Advaita assigns practitioner effort to the preparatory disciplines but self-luminous recognition to the moment of moksha. If most traditions distribute credit differently at different stages, the typology may describe phases rather than stable tradition-level properties. This would not refute the variable, but it would require recasting the model as a stage-level rather than tradition-level variable.
observations/claude/2026-05-26-whose-doing-is-this-credit-distribution-as-a-practice-variable.md:Second, the failure-mode predictions may be too neat. Real traditions combine safeguards against multiple dangers. Buddhism warns against spiritual pride (from its practitioner-centered effort) but also against passivity (in the story of Sona, MN 55, who was told to tune the string neither too tight nor too loose). The Gita warns against strategic detachment but also against spiritual pride (Chapter 16 on asuric qualities). If every tradition guards against every failure mode, the prediction that credit distribution determines the primary danger loses specificity. The model would need to show that the primary safeguard consistently matches the credit type, not merely that one of many safeguards does.
observations/claude/2026-05-26-whose-doing-is-this-credit-distribution-as-a-practice-variable.md:Fourth, the Gita comparison may overweight one interpretive strand. BG 3.27 on prakriti as doer sits alongside BG 18.14, which lists five causes of action (the body, the individual soul, the various senses, the various functions, and the divine as the fifth cause). The Gita's own credit distribution is contested among Advaita, Vishishtadvaita, and Dvaita commentators. Using one verse as representative of 'the Gita's position' is a simplification that primary-text close-reading should resist.
observations/claude/2026-05-26-whose-doing-is-this-credit-distribution-as-a-practice-variable.md:Sixth, the strongest anomaly may be dual-trained practitioners who report no dissonance when switching credit distributions. If a practitioner trained in both Theravada vipassana and Dzogchen reports smooth transitions without experiencing different agency orientations, either the credit-distribution variable is less operationally important than claimed, or practitioners develop a meta-capacity for switching credit orientations that the model does not account for. The successful hybrids noted in the frontier brief (practitioners who switch methods smoothly without reported directional resistance) are a direct pressure on this model.
observations/claude/2026-05-26-whose-doing-is-this-credit-distribution-as-a-practice-variable.md:- Test the stage-shifting objection directly: code Theravada, Sufi, and Advaita practice sequences for credit distribution at each stage. If credit shifts predictably (e.g., practitioner-centered early, ground-centered or source-centered late), the model should be revised from a tradition-level variable to a stage-level variable. This revision would actually increase explanatory power by predicting that the transition between credit types is the moment of highest practice vulnerability.
observations/claude/2026-05-26-whose-doing-is-this-credit-distribution-as-a-practice-variable.md:- Compare credit distribution with the capacity ledger to test whether they are genuinely separable variables. If two traditions can share a capacity-ledger profile (same required capacities, same load-holders) while differing in credit distribution, the variables are separable and both are needed for the frontier rubric. If credit distribution always determines the capacity profile, one may be reducible to the other.
observations/claude/2026-05-26-whose-doing-is-this-credit-distribution-as-a-practice-variable.md:- Protocol improvement: before comparing traditions on effort, first name the credit distribution each operates under, and ask whether the researcher's own assumed credit distribution is shaping which evidence looks convincing. A researcher who assumes practitioner-centered credit will find source-centered paths harder to take seriously, and vice versa. The nishkama karma lens used here revealed this bias: it made split-credit positions feel most natural.

