# Originality Audit: The Forbidden Claimant Rubric

Audit ID: ccc236ff67de7a3f
Idea ID: c53042c11562b839
Agent: codex
Created: 2026-05-26T14:48:17-07:00
Status: extended
Confidence: 0.83

## Exact Claim

The effort-gift boundary is not how much the practitioner does, but who is allowed to claim the doing. Each path requires functions such as receiving, agency, memory, reflexivity, and integration, while assigning their support to a practitioner, teacher, vow, name, text, community, present act, awareness itself, or later integration, and explicitly forbidding some claimant from owning the function.

## Claim Units

- A path can require real functions while forbidding ordinary self-ownership of those functions.
- The right audit unit is a two-part code: support locus plus forbidden claimant.
- Right effort, Other Power, direct introduction, and practice-realization differ by which functions are required and which owner is disallowed.
- Gift paths should not be translated into hidden self-power, but every path must carry the work somewhere.
- Wrong-claimant failures should predict distinctive practice errors and adverse patterns.

## Primary Text Close Read

Sources:
- SN 45.8 Magga-vibhanga Sutta, right effort, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN45_8.html
- Shinran, Letter to Senshin, Other Power, https://shinranworks.com/letters/a-collection-of-letters-zensho-text/what-we-call-other-power/

Structural observation: SN 45.8 makes the practitioner the grammatical agent of desire, persistence, intent, prevention, abandonment, cultivation, and maintenance. Shinran's Letter to Senshin makes settled shinjin incompatible with calculation on the practicer's side, and says no working is true working. This comparison supports the function-claimant split: practice can retain necessary operations while changing who may claim them. But the split is already explicit in the primary materials, especially in Shinran, so the rubric mostly generalizes an old tension rather than discovering it.

Secondary literature gap: The closest structural gap is not self-power versus other-power, which is well known, but the per-function grid of support locus plus prohibited claimant. Still, Pargament's religious coping styles, religious locus of control, Christian monergism and synergism, Sri Vaishnava markata and marjara, Buddhist upaya, Engler's ego-strength thesis, and prior Lumenary capacity-ledger work already occupy much of the architecture.

Risk of overread: High. Claimant language may impose an ownership grammar on traditions that speak in terms of karma, grace, vow, emptiness, devotion, non-contrivance, or conventional truth. The model also risks flattening stage changes: the same action may be self-power before awakening, natural expression after awakening, and conventional compassion in public teaching.

## Literature Search Queries

- Pargament religious coping self-directing deferring collaborative God control
- religious locus of control God control active passive spiritual health locus of control
- Shinran Other Power self power calculation hakarai entrusting mind
- monergism synergism grace works human cooperation divine agency
- markata marjara nyaya prapatti grace effort Sri Vaishnavism
- Dogen practice realization one Bendowa gaining idea
- Chinul sudden awakening gradual cultivation practice based on enlightenment
- Lindahl Britton varieties contemplative experience adverse meditation teacher support interpretation

## Near Neighbors

- Kenneth Pargament et al., religious coping styles, summarized in https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1630686/ and https://link.springer.com/rwe/10.1007/978-3-030-24348-7_578: overlap: Very close structural neighbor. Pargament's self-directing, deferring, and collaborative styles already ask whether responsibility for change rests with the person, God, or both.; difference: The claimant rubric moves from coping and perceived control to soteriological practice functions, and adds the negative field of which owner is forbidden to claim a function.; novelty impact: High reduction. The main variable, allocation of responsibility, is already modeled empirically.
- Religious locus of control and spiritual-health locus of control, overview at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Locus_of_control and related God-control literature: overlap: Close. Internal, external, God-empowered, and God-deferred control map directly onto support locus and agency attribution.; difference: Locus-of-control literature does not usually close-read practice manuals or distinguish support holder from forbidden claimant in contemplative training.; novelty impact: High reduction for support-locus originality, moderate preservation for the manual-coding rubric.
- Shinran, Other Power and hakarai, https://shinranworks.com/glossary/ and https://shinranworks.com/letters/a-collection-of-letters-zensho-text/what-we-call-other-power/: overlap: Near exact for source-centered paths. Shinran already separates entrusting from self-powered calculation and treats the practicer's claim as the problem.; difference: The Lumenary idea generalizes this to multiple functions and traditions rather than keeping it inside Jodo Shinshu.; novelty impact: High reduction. The forbidden-claimant idea is strongly present in Shinran.
- Christian monergism and synergism, overview at https://www.monergism.com/what-monergism-vs-synergism: overlap: Close. The debate asks whether salvation is God's work alone or cooperative, and whether faith itself is caused by divine action.; difference: The claimant rubric is broader than Christian regeneration and allows non-theistic and activity-centered support loci.; novelty impact: High reduction for the core agency question, some novelty remains in cross-tradition operationalization.
- Sri Vaishnava markata and marjara nyaya, example overview at https://philosophy.institute/indian-philosophy/visistadvaita-path-liberation-bhakti-prapatti/: overlap: Close indigenous near-neighbor. The monkey and kitten analogies already encode different distributions of effort and grace.; difference: The rubric adds multiple support functions and forbidden claimant warnings beyond a two-model grace debate.; novelty impact: Moderate to high reduction, especially for the claim that traditions themselves divide over this variable.
- Buddhist upaya and capacity-sensitive teaching, Bhikkhu Analayo, Skill in Means and Mindfulness, https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s12671-021-01795-2, and Harvard Divinity Bulletin on Buddhist skillful means, https://bulletin.hds.harvard.edu/buddhist-studies-the-buddhist-way/: overlap: Close background. Upaya already treats teaching and practice as adapted to capacities, safeguards, and current limitations.; difference: Upaya does not by itself ask who may claim the required function, only which means fits the practitioner.; novelty impact: Moderate reduction.
- Local Lumenary prior, The Capacity Ledger of Gift and Effort, plus The Grain of Capacity, cited in the prompt: overlap: Near exact internal neighbor. The capacity ledger already asks where receiving, agency, memory, reflexivity, and integration are held across practitioner, vow, teacher, present act, and post-insight integration.; difference: The new rubric adds a sharper prohibited-owner column, but mostly develops the same architecture.; novelty impact: Very high internal reduction. This should be merged rather than published as independent.
- Chinul, Secrets on Cultivating the Mind, https://www.themathesontrust.org/papers/buddhism/Chinul-Secrets_on_Cultivating_the_Mind.pdf: overlap: Close anomaly-neighbor. Sudden awakening followed by gradual cultivation already requires necessary practice without treating practice as ultimate production.; difference: Chinul gives a stage-sensitive soteriology, not a cross-tradition function grid.; novelty impact: Moderate reduction and strong pressure to make the rubric stage-based.

## Unlike Statement

Unlike Pargament, religious locus-of-control work, self-power and other-power debates, monergism and synergism, and the local capacity ledger, this idea says that each required practice function should be coded twice: where the function is operationally supported and which claimant the tradition forbids from owning it.

## Anomaly Probe

Candidate: Chinul's sudden awakening and gradual cultivation, plus radical Jodo Shinshu Other Power.

Why it strains the model: Chinul makes the same cultivation necessary after awakening but empty of production, so the claimant status changes by stage. Shinran makes even entrusting wholly Other Power, so calling vow, hearing, or trust a support locus may be an analyst's domestication of grace. These cases strain any clean grid that treats support and claimant as stable cells.

Confidence effect: Lowers confidence from candidate-discovery range to extended. The rubric remains useful, but only if it becomes stage-sensitive and allows traditions to reject the analyst's ownership vocabulary.

## Falsifiable Predictions

- If: Practice manuals should warn not only about missing capacity, but about a necessary function being claimed by the wrong owner. Then: Pure Land texts warn against self-power calculation, Zen texts warn against gaining idea or contrivance, Advaita texts warn against egoic doership or premature realization, and effort-centered Buddhist texts warn against claiming aggregates as self while still authorizing cultivation. Weakens if: Manual warnings cluster around generic ethics, obedience, humility, or community order, with no recurring relation to wrong-claimant patterns. Test surface: Blind coding of manuals from Jodo Shinshu, Theravada, Soto Zen, Dzogchen, Advaita, and Sri Vaishnava prapatti.
- If: Dual-trained practitioners should report shifts in permitted first-person grammar when changing methods. Then: Practitioners distinguish felt modes such as I cultivate, I entrust, I recognize, I just sit, or this is not mine, and they can name which phrasing would feel doctrinally or practically wrong in each method. Weakens if: Practitioners report only generic differences in calm, concentration, devotion, or teacher style, with no felt shift in agency or claimant grammar. Test surface: Micro-phenomenological interviews with dual-trained practitioners, coded before doctrinal explanation is invited.
- If: Adverse practice events should sometimes cluster around wrong-claimant failures. Then: Gift practice shows self-power anxiety or false surrender, direct-introduction practice shows reification of recognition, practice-realization shows achievement seeking or empty formalism, and effort practice shows pride or mechanical striving. Weakens if: Adverse reports are fully explained by trauma history, retreat intensity, sleep loss, psychiatric vulnerability, poor supervision, or social isolation, with no added value from claimant coding. Test surface: Re-coding VCE-style interviews and teacher case consultations for prior training, current method, claimant language, and failure type.

## Practitioner Test

Relevant practitioners:
- Jodo Shinshu ministers
- Theravada insight teachers
- Soto Zen teachers
- Dzogchen or Mahamudra teachers
- Advaita Vedanta teachers
- Sri Vaishnava teachers familiar with prapatti
- Contemplative clinicians familiar with meditation-related adverse effects
- Psychologists of religion familiar with Pargament

Questions:
- Is support locus plus forbidden claimant already obvious as self-power, other-power, doership, gaining idea, pride, upaya, or ordinary lineage pedagogy?
- For receiving, agency, memory, reflexivity, and integration, can you name who or what carries the function in your training, and who must not claim it?
- Would this rubric change how you sequence practice, diagnose student errors, or warn cross-trained practitioners?

Answers that reduce originality: Teachers say the rubric merely renames standard warnings, or psychologists say it is Pargament and locus-of-control language applied to contemplative texts. Practitioners find claimant language alien or misleading.

Answers that support contribution: Teachers can use the grid to predict previously missed failure modes, especially in cross-training, and can identify function-specific wrong-claimant warnings in primary manuals before seeing the model.

## Cross-Domain Prediction

Domain: Identity-transforming therapy and recovery programs

Structural translation: Support may be held by client agency, therapist, group, protocol, medicine, higher power, present-session enactment, or integration practice, while some claimant is warned not to take sole credit.

Prediction: Programs with similar behavioral tasks but different claimant rules should produce different failure modes: self-help over-ownership, passive surrender, therapist dependency, medicine-as-savior attribution, or empty compliance with protocol.

Would count against it: Ordinary skills training shows the same claimant safeguards and failure modes, or therapy outcomes are predicted by alliance, dosage, diagnosis, and social support without any added value from claimant coding.

## Score Recommendations

- novelty: 0.45
- source_reliability: 0.84
- counterargument_quality: 0.91

Novelty adjustment: Reduce novelty from 0.57 to about 0.45. The prohibited-claimant column is useful, but the main structure is strongly anticipated by self-power and other-power, monergism and synergism, Pargament's religious coping styles, locus-of-control research, Sri Vaishnava grace-effort debates, and local capacity-ledger work.

## Next Loop Instructions

- Merge this record with the capacity-ledger and credit-distribution records rather than publishing it as independent.
- Read Pargament et al. on religious problem-solving styles directly before claiming novelty.
- Build the coding sheet with fields for function, stage, support locus, forbidden claimant, safeguard, and failure mode.
- Code primary manuals before broad tradition labels, especially SN 45.8, Shinran letters, Tannisho, Bendowa, Chinul, Longchen Rabjam, and Sri Vaishnava prapatti sources.
- Add an explicit value for traditions or stages that reject the claimant frame itself.
- Do not promote above extended unless practitioner interviews show the rubric predicts sequencing or failure patterns not already explained by religious coping, upaya, or lineage pedagogy.

